.sp 0
.sp 0


.SH 2. NUMERIC
.SH

.SS
if (var.isnum()) ...
.PP
Check if a var is numeric.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR True if a var holds a double, integer, or a string representing a numeric value.
.sp 0
.PP
A string is considered numeric if it is:
.sp 0
.br
\(bu Empty (treated as zero), or
.br
\(bu Composed of one or more digits (0-9), an optional leading '+' or '-' sign, and an optional single decimal point ('.') placed before, within, or after the digits.
.br
\(bu Optionally includes an exponential suffix ('e' or 'E', optionally followed by '+' or '-', and 1-3 digits).
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
if (   "+123.45"_var.isnum()) ... ok
if ("+1.2345e+2"_var.isnum()) ... ok
if (          ""_var.isnum()) ... ok
if (not      "."_var.isnum()) ... ok
// or
if (isnum("123.")) ... ok
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
var v1 = var.num();
.PP
Copy a var if it is numeric or 0 if not.
.sp 0
.PP
This allows working numerically with data that may be non-numeric.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR A guaranteed numeric var
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
var v1 = "123.45"_var.num();    // 123.45
var v2 = "abc"_var.num() + 100; // 100
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
var v1 = + v1;
.PP
Unary plus.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR The numeric value of a variable or expression, or throws a VarNonNumeric error.
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
let v1 = 3;
let v2 = +v1; // 3
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
var v1 = - v1;
.PP
Unary minus.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR The negative of a numeric variable or expression, or throws a VarNonNumeric error. Negative of a negative is a positive.
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
let v1 = 3;
let v2 = -v1; // -3
let v3 = -v2; // 3
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
if (! v1) ...
.PP
Boolean negate.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBAlias:\fR "not" as in "if (not ...)".
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR True if a variable or expression is false, or False if it is true.
.sp 0
.PP
Negate the result of the following:
.sp 0
.PD 0 \"<dl>
.TP 10\"<dt>
\fBEmpty string\fR \"</dt>
false
.\"</dd>
.TP 10\"<dt>
\fBNon-numeric string\fR \"</dt>
true
.\"</dd>
.TP 10\"<dt>
\fBZero (string or number)\fR \"</dt>
false
.\"</dd>
.TP 10\"<dt>
\fBNon-zero (string or number)\fR \"</dt>
true
.\"</dd>
.PD \"</dl>
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
if (!var("") eq true) ... ok
if (!var("x") eq false) ... ok
if (!var("0") eq true) ... ok
if (!var("123") eq false) ... ok
// or
if (not var("") eq true) ... ok
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
v1 ++
.PP
Post-increment
.sp 0
.PP
++ and -- are only allowed on named variables, not expressions, to prevent writing cryptic and buggy code.
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
var v1 = 3;
let v2 = v1++; // v2 -> 3 // v1 -> 4
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
v1 --
.PP
Post-decrement
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
var v1 = 3;
let v2 = v1--; // v2 -> 3 // v1 -> 2
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
++ v1
.PP
Pre-increment
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
