.SH 1. OS TIME/DATE
.SH

.SS
var v1 = var::date();
.PP
Get the current date in internal format.
.sp 0
.PP
Internal format is the number of whole days since pick epoch 1967-12-31 00:00:00 UTC. Dates prior to that are numbered negatively.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR A number. e.g. 20821 represents 2025-01-01 00:00:00 UTC for 24 hours.
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
let today1 = var::date();
// or
let today2 = date();
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
var v1 = var::time();
.PP
Get the current time in internal format.
.sp 0
.PP
Internal time is the number of whole seconds since the last midnight 00:00:00 (UTC).
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR A number in the range 0 - 86399 since there are 24*60*60 seconds in a day. e.g. 43200 if time is 12:00:00
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
let now1 = var::time();
// or
let now2 = time();
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
var v1 = var::ostime();
.PP
Get the current time in high resolution internal format.
.sp 0
.PP
High resolution internal time is the number of fractional seconds since the last midnight 00:00:00 (UTC).
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR A floating point with approx. nanosecond resolution depending on hardware.
.sp 0
.PP
e.g. 23343.704387955 approx. 06:29:03 UTC
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
let now1 = var::ostime();
// or
let now2 = ostime();
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
var v1 = var::ostimestamp();
.PP
Get the current timestamp in internal format.
.sp 0
.PP
Internal timestamp is the number of fractional days since pick epoch 1967-12-31 00:00:00 UTC. Negative for dates before.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR A floating point with approx. nanosecond resolution depending on hardware.
.sp 0
.PP
e.g. Was 20821.99998842593 around 2025-01-01 23:59:59 UTC
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
let now1 = var::ostimestamp();
// or
let now2 = ostimestamp();
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
var v1 = vardate.ostimestamp(ostime);
.PP
Get the timestamp for a given date and time
.sp 0
.PP
\fBvardate:\fR Internal date from date(), iconv("D") etc.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBostime:\fR Internal time from time(), ostime(), iconv("MT") etc.
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
let idate = iconv("2025-01-01", "D"), itime = iconv("23:59:59", "MT");
let ts1 = idate.ostimestamp(itime); // 20821.99998842593
// or
let ts2 = ostimestamp(idate, itime);
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
var::ossleep(milliseconds)
.PP
Sleep/pause/wait
.sp 0
.PP
\fBmilliseconds:\fR How to long to sleep.
.sp 0
.PP
Release the processor if not needed for a period of time or a delay is required.
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
var::ossleep(100); // sleep for 100ms
// or
ossleep(100);
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0


.SS
var v1 = file_dir_list.oswait(milliseconds);
.PP
Sleep/pause/wait up for a file system event
.sp 0
.PP
\fBfile_dir_list:\fR An FM delimited list of OS files and/or dirs to monitor.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBmilliseconds:\fR How long to wait. Any terminal input (e.g. a key press) will also terminate the wait.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBreturn:\fR An FM array of event information is returned. See below.
.sp 0
.PP
Multiple events may be captured and are returned in multivalues.
.sp 0
.PP
.PP
\fBExample:\fR
.EX \"<code>
let v1 = ".^/etc/hosts"_var.oswait(100); /// e.g. "IN_CLOSE_WRITE^/etc^hosts^f"_var
// or
let v2 = oswait(".^/etc/hosts"_var, 100);
.EE \"</code>
.sp 0
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
Returned dynamic array fields:
