.TH task_manager.h

.SH 1. ASYNC TASKS 
.SH

.SS
async(funcname, args, ...)
.PP
Create an independent asynchronous task by calling a function.
.sp 0
.PP
\fBfuncname:\fR Any callable function name. To call an Exodus program member function, it must be prefixed by "&_ExoProgram::" and followed by ", this" as follows:
.sp 0
.PP
e.g. async(&_ExoProgram::xxxxxx, this, arg1, arg2, etc)
.sp 0
.PP
All async functions started within a thread/job share a single copy of environment variables, RECORD, ID, ANS etc.
.sp 0
.PP
Exodus' asynchronous tasks run sequentially, not simultaneously. Their execution will be interleaved with other async tasks in the same thread of execution. Execution switches (yields) either when a task asks for database i/o or when it explicitly calls yield(). Tasks are implicitly thread-safe but environment variables like RECORD, ID, ANS are thread-wide and shared by all async tasks in a thread.
.sp 0
.PP
Exodus' asynchronous tasks are implemented using Boost fibers. These are similar to threads but without parallel processing or OS management. They are extremely fast to setup and and switch between and have a normal stack. They might be called "coprocesses" by comparion with "coroutines" which do not have stacks.
.sp 0
.PP
The initial state of an asynchronous task is "ready, not running". Once the main program calls yield() then one of the "ready, not running" async tasks is selected by a round robin scheduler and it runs until complete, requests database i/o, or yields, and so on.
.sp 0
.PP
Asynchronous tasks may return results in a result queue by calling set_async_result(...) one or more times.
.sp 0
.PP
Asynchronous tasks may use the default database connection, which is per thread, but not at the same time so they should create their own connection. Multiple asynchronous tasks using multiple asynchronous database connections is the prime use case for async tasks since while some tasks are waiting for db i/o another task can progress.
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
\fBhttps://x.com/i/grok/share/N4zbWT3V2hb4qK71G0qT0togh\fR
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
\fBConcept:\fR "async" aligns with the computer science concept of *cooperative multitasking*, where isolated execution contexts yield to a scheduler for *interleaved*, not simultaneous, execution.
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
\fBAsynchronous:\fR Interleaved execution of multiple tasks (with full stacks) within a *single thread*, not parallelism (simultaneous multi-CPU execution).
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
\fBFull Stack:\fR Independent, full execution context sharing global state but with separate call stacks, resembling process-like entities but not OS processes. Not lightweight coroutines (e.g., Python‚Äôs 'async def' or generators) due to their lack of isolation and stacks.
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
\fBYield:\fR Each async task can yield control explicitly to the task scheduler, suspending its own execution and allowing another tasks/stack to run.
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
\fBScheduler:\fR
.sp 0
.PP
.br
\(bu A *minimal, non-interrupt-driven* mechanism that scans async full stacks and decide which to run next.
.br
\(bu Its sole role is to *pass control* (or "hand the baton") to the next task, not to manage events (e.g., I/O, timers, or signals).
.br
\(bu May optionally link to events if chosen, but this is not its primary function.
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
\fBNo OS:\fR No OS-level process creation (e.g., no 'fork', 'spawn', or equivalents like Python‚Äôs 'multiprocessing').
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
\fBNo Threads:\fR Multiple async tasks share a *single thread*. Threads can have multiple async routines but not vice versa.
.sp 0
.PP
.sp 0
.PP
\fBNo Stackless Coroutines:\fR Lightweight cooperative tasks (e.g., Python‚Äôs 'asyncio' coroutines or generators) are not considered full stacks
.sp 0
.PP
